[6]
Date: Tue, 08 Apr 2003 13:43:20 -0400
From: Judith Johnson <JAJOHNSON@crs.loc.gov>

We read with interest the moderator comment copied below.
[To place these figures in perspective, China (including Hong Kong) has now
reported 69 deaths in 4.5 months. In 122 cities in the USA, with a total
population much less than one quarter of China's population, there have now
been 890 deaths from pneumonia + influenza reported in the 3 months ending
29 Mar 2003 -- see: <http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5213md.htm>
Table III. - Mod.JW]
We believe that the 890 deaths mentioned in the comment actually represents
deaths in one week (week 13) in the U.S. in the 122 cities rather than
during the 3 months ending 29 Mar 2003. Curious, we looked further. Table
32 (page 127) of Health, United States, 2002 indicates that in 1999 there
were 63 730 pneumonia + influenza (P+I) deaths in the U.S., (weekly average
of 1226 deaths). Table 33 (page 132) indicates that of this total, 57 282
P + I deaths occurred in persons over 65 years of age (weekly average 1102
deaths), and therefore 6448 deaths occurred in persons under 65 years of
age (weekly average of 124 deaths). In the 25-44 years age group there
were 1402 deaths caused by P + I in 1999 (weekly average of 27
deaths). These back-of-the-envelope calculations give an even more
striking perspective to numbers of SARS deaths.
Judith A. Johnson and Pamela W. Smith
--
Judith A. Johnson
Congressional Research Service
The Library of Congress
101 Independence Ave., S.E.
Washington, DC 20540-7440
<JAJOHNSON@crs.loc.gov>
[ProMED-mail would like to thank JA Johnson and PW Smith for the correction
and for further highlighting the current disparities in reported deaths due
to SARS when compared with reported deaths due to P + I. - Mod.MPP]
