Source: News briefs [edited]
[A] South Africa
Date: Tue, 8 Apr 2003 08:29:58 +0200
From: Steve Toovey <toovey@travelclinic.co.za>

Medinfo reports that the first probable SARS case has been reported in
Pretoria. A 62-year-old gentleman with a recent history of travel to China
was admitted to the Pretoria East hospital on 7 Apr 2003 with symptoms
suggestive of SARS. He was immediately recognised as a potential SARS case
and placed into isolation. He is currently being managed strictly according
to WHO and CDC recommendations.
Definitive virological tests are being conducted at the moment, and the
Department of Health has been informed. Dr Andrew Jamieson of Netcare
Travel Clinics confirmed the admission. The patient is in a critical
condition and is being ventilated.
[ProMED-mail appreciates this first hand report of the first probable case
of SARS in South Africa, and on the African continent. - Mod.MPP
[B] China - Guangdong from Xinhuanet 9 Apr 2003 00:46
AM <http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2003-04/09/content_822052.htm>
According to the provincial health department, Guangdong reported 10 new
cases of the epidemic on 1 Apr 2003 and only one case on 7 Apr 2003. The
average number of cases reported from 1 to 7 April 2003 was 7.57, down
70.2 percent from the same period last month. Currently 82.3 percent of
patients in the province have recovered and left hospital.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to the WHO worldwide update, "as of today, 2671 SARS cases with
103 deaths have been reported from 17 countries. This represents an
increase of 70 cases and 5 deaths when compared with yesterday. The new
deaths were reported in Canada (1), Hong Kong SAR (2), and Singapore (2).
The additional cases were reported in Canada (1), China (11), Hong Kong SAR
(45), France (1), Singapore (7), and the United States (7). Taiwan, China
removed 2 cases from the list."
In the Health Canada update [4] there are reports of 3 additional probable
cases since the report contained in the WHO update, and in the CDC data
from the USA [5], there is one additional case since the report to WHO
(because of the time zone differences, these additional cases will appear
in tomorrow's WHO update). In the brief section above [7][A], we have a
report of the first probable case of SARS in South Africa, also
representing the first reported case on the African continent.
The newswire report from China on the daily case count in Guangdong
decreasing is interesting. We look forward to the report from the WHO
team's visit to Guangdong for more detailed information on the epidemiology
of SARS in the 5-month period since its first recognition. - Mod.MPP]
